For some features, ratio of NaN values is ridiculous. These features are PoolQC, MiscFeature, Alley, Fence, FirePlaceQu. However, we choose to keep these features instead of simply deleting them because we believe that they have a real added value to the house.

We have to deal with these NaN values. 'NA' attributes have been misgiven for Nulls, we thus have to replace them accoridingly if it's a numerical feature or a categorical feature.

There are three numerical feature where there are Nan values, two of them are surfaces, so it makes sense to put a zero instead of a NaN. The feature GarageYrBlt is disturbing, it is a date, so replacing NaN by a zero will be dangerous. We choose then to delete this column. Plus, it doesn't add up much information.

However, we have to deal with all the features (pretending that we don't have access to the test set). For the numerical features, there should not be a problem. We'll replace all by 0 since they are all surfaces, or prices, except for MoSold, YrSold, YearBuilt and YearRemodAdd that should all be filled.

For the categorical features, we'll only replace all by 'NA' as intended in the original dataset.

In [0]:
dataset = dataset.drop('GarageYrBlt' , axis=1) #dropping the column GarageYrBlt another way would be to use knn or mice (if we have time)

categorical_features = list(dataset.select_dtypes(include=object).columns)
numerical_features = list(dataset.select_dtypes(exclude=object).columns)

dataset[numerical_features] = dataset[numerical_features].fillna(0) #filling Nan values with 0

dataset[categorical_features] = dataset[categorical_features].fillna('NA') #filling Nan values with NA as intended in the dataset

We dealt with all the NaN values, now we have to treat all the categorical features, replacing them with numerical features, or do some k-encoding.

1.1.1.b. Categorical features encoding¶

We choose to do both techniques, convert some features into numerical features, and convert other features into many cloumns with boolean values (k-encoding). We will do this to try to limit the number of added columns, when we can replace into a numerical feature, we'll do so. This will be the case when there is a potential scale (Ex, Gd, TA, Fa, Po for example).

In this section, we deal with the categorical features that can be ordered in a certain scale. It is a bit dangerous to assume that these features have a linear scale, and could alter our results. However, it reduces greatly our number of features.

In [0]:
categorical_features_scale1 = ['ExterQual', 'ExterCond', 
                               'BsmtCond','BsmtQual',
                               'HeatingQC','KitchenQual','FireplaceQu',
                               'GarageQual','GarageCond','PoolQC']   
categorical_features_scale2 = ['BsmtExposure']
categorical_features_scale3 = ['BsmtFinType1', 'BsmtFinType2']
categorical_features_scale4 = ['CentralAir']

scale1 = {'NA':np.nan,'Po':2, 'Fa':3, 'TA':4, 'Gd':5, 'Ex':6}
scale2 = {'NA':np.nan, 'No':2, 'Mn':3, 'Av':4, 'Gd':5}
scale3 = {'NA':np.nan, 'Unf':2, 'LwQ':3, 'Rec':4, 'BLQ':5, 'ALQ':6, 'GLQ':7}
scale4 = {'N':0, 'Y':1}

for feature in categorical_features_scale1:
  dataset[feature] = [scale1[item] for item in dataset[feature]]

for feature in categorical_features_scale2:
  dataset[feature] = [scale2[item] for item in dataset[feature]]

for feature in categorical_features_scale3:
  dataset[feature] = [scale3[item] for item in dataset[feature]]

for feature in categorical_features_scale4:
  dataset[feature] = [scale4[item] for item in dataset[feature]]

Now, let's fill the NaN values with an algorithm to not falsify too much our data. We'll use the Mice algorithm. Since it applies only to numerical values, we only keep that. It then attributes a value to the NaNs values so that they do not alter the overall distribution.

1.1.2. Data visualization¶

For the data visualization, we'll work on the original train dataset, it makes more sense, since the original features have more sense to us than the ones we created.

1.1.2.a. Sale Price analysis¶
In [25]:
train_vis['SalePrice'].describe()
Out[25]:

The Sale Price mean is around 180 000$ (assuming it's in the American market). Also, the minimum is 34 900$ and the maximum 755 000$ with a standard deviation of 81 000$ which is quite high. We can say then that the range of houses is large, and our dataset diverse.

As said in the descriptive notebook: "The evaluation method for this challenge is the root mean squared error between the logarithm of the predicted value and the logarithm of the observed sales price. Taking logs ensures that errors in predicting expensive houses and cheap houses will have a similar impact on the overall result."

Indeed, the normal/Gaussian assumption is used because it is the most computationally convenient choice. This is a quadratic minimization problem (we compute the RMSE) and can be solved using pure linear algebra. It this case, normality is then a good assumption because it provides us good properties that will probably work well for regression.

However, it has its drawbacks compared to other distributions. It is very sesnsitive to outliers, we'll have to be careful to remove them, in order to not distort our model.

Let's look at the Sale Price distribution, and the log(Sale Price) Distribution.

In [0]:
%matplotlib inline
In [27]:

plt.title('Sale Price Distribution')
sns.distplot(train_vis['SalePrice'])
plt.subplot(1,2,2)
plt.title('Log of the Sale Price Distribution')
sns.distplot(np.log(train_vis['SalePrice']))
plt.show()

As said before, we can notice that the Sale Price distribution's deviates a bit from the Sale Price distribution. Taking the log gives us a curve that is much more similar to a normal distribution.

2.1.2. Defining a cross-validation strategy and testing it on various models¶

Here, we define a function using a cross-validation strategy, in order to validate more accurately our models. Using KFold and shuffling(cross-validation) and using cross_val_score with the right scoring.

In [0]:
#Validation function
n_folds = 5

def rmse_cv(model, X, y):
    kf = KFold(n_folds, shuffle=True, random_state=42).get_n_splits(X)
    rmse = -cross_val_score(model, X, y, scoring="neg_root_mean_squared_error", cv = kf)
    return(rmse)

This gives us all the parameters currently used in the random forest. There are a bit much and running a tuner on all these parameters would take a while. Reading the documentation of RandomForestRegressor, the most importants parameters seem to be:

  • n_estimators: number of trees in the forest
  • max_depth: The maximum depth of the tree
  • min_samples_split: The minimum number of samples required to split an internal node
  • min_samples_leaf: The minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node

In order to choose the hyperparameters, we'll use a GridSearchCV, we create a parameter grid.

In [63]:
n_estimators = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(start = 400, stop = 800, num = 5)]
max_depth = [int(x) for x in np.linspace(10, 40, num = 3)]
max_depth.append(None)
min_samples_split = [4, 5, 6]
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]

random_grid = {'n_estimators': n_estimators,
               'max_depth': max_depth,
               'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,
               'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf}
pprint(random_grid)

def testing_models(models, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, iterations = 100):
    results = {}
    results['Metric'] = ['R2_train', 'R2_test', 'RMSE_train', 'RMSE_test', 'Running time (s)']
    for i in models:
        r2_train = []
        r2_test = []
        rmsecv_train = []
        rmsecv_test = []
        run_time = []

        for j in range(iterations):

            start_train = time()
            model_trained = models[i].fit(X_train, y_train)
            end_train = time()
            time_train = end_train - start_train
            run_time.append(time_train)

            r2_test.append(r2_score(y_test,model_trained.predict(X_test)))
            r2_train.append(r2_score(y_train, model_trained.predict(X_train)))

            rmsecv_test.append(np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, model_trained.predict(X_test))))
            rmsecv_train.append(np.mean(rmse_cv(model_trained, X_train, y_train)))

        results[i] = [np.mean(r2_train),
                      np.mean(r2_test),
                      np.mean(rmsecv_train),
                      np.mean(rmsecv_test),
                      np.mean(run_time)]
    return pd.DataFrame(results)
